# Sourdough

Date: 2026-02-23

Sourdough bread might be the breadiest of bread, consisting of only salt, water and flour. After seeing all the buzz and hype around sourdough bread and all it's variants, I was hesistant to try as I was never a fan of sour bread, not did I particularly care for the community. My first sourdough bread was in Ottawa from Loblaws. At around $5 a boule, it was soft and slightly sour and toasted beautifully. It was delicious with bruschetta, slice of cheese, chicken breast, or a fried egg. 

Fast forward to October of last year, I was bored out of my mind during a seminar at work and decided to start a sourdough starter. I had read that there is a million-and-one opinions online about sourdough and that you'd quickly get overwhelmed with all the contrasting opinions. Not a lie was told. I ended up following the [sourdough starter recipe by The Clever Carrot](https://www.theclevercarrot.com/2019/03/beginner-sourdough-starter-recipe/). All recipes are more or less exactly the same, since it is just 1:1 ratio of flour and water initially, then 1:1:1 ratio of starter to flour to water. Take [King Arthur's starter recipe](https://www.kingarthurbaking.com/recipes/sourdough-starter-recipe) for example. I remember it initially stated like 100g of flour each feeding which would've left you with a massive jar full. Unsurprisingly, the just updated their recipe to only produce a small amount. If I could do it all over again, I would've started with a much much smaller amount. Instead of 60g, just 10g would have been more than plenty. 

My starter took exactly 10 days for it to show signs of rise, bubbling, and yeast activity! It looked terrible for the day 9 days and I was so sure that it failed that I had started a new starter on the 9th day. What a pleasant surprise it was to wake up on the 10th day to see it had doubled in size and had a sweet, yeasted smell instead of the lactic acid tang. From then on, I drastically reduced my starter amount. I had initially settled on 10g:10g:10g but found that my starter was rather sour instead of the described yeasted scent like freshly baked bread. I came upon an Instagram post that recommended a feeding of 1:3:2 to provide more nutrients. Other sources also said that lower hydration starters improved acidity. I don't follow 1:3:2 perfectly as I find it way too thick like bread dough (possibly because I'm using whole wheat flour?). I do however, measure 1:2 ratio of starter to flour then eyeball water until the texture resembles a thick oatmeal, just barely pourable. I find the rise and acidity to be much better now, with the downside of more sourdough discard. Luckily, the discard is well used up in morning glory muffins or waffles (yay waffle machine!) so no waste here :)


### The bakes

Technically my first sourdough bake was my sourdough bagels which turned out pretttyyyy bad. It was completely underproofed and sank to the bottom when boiling... ended up tasting half decent after baking but was totally dense and tough. Not my best work and I will try again some day...

My first real bake would be a sourdough cheddar loaf

